@DataBase CFG_Commands_System

@Index HBBS:Docs/Misc/Index.guide/MAIN

@Node Main "HBBS:Commands/System"

  Description:

  The "HBBS:Commands/System" file, and other ".../Commands/System" files
  like the ones that go in "HBBS:Nodes/NodeXX/Commands/System" and
  "HBBS:Conferences/<ConfName>/Commands/System", are used to define
  the system commands.

  A system command/system door as a program that is started by either
  the node program or via another door.

  In contrast to a user command/user door's that are started by the user
  from the BBS's command prompt.

  For example, FR is a user command that starts the filelister,
  whereas CmdPrompt is a system command started by node that starts the
  command prompt.

  A system door and a user door are programmed in the same way, and
  some doors are in fact system doors and user doors, for example
  the JoinCon and the J door can use the same executable and are
  defined in both the Commands/System file and a Commands/#?Level#? file.

  The files are normal config files, and the options are thus:

  <SystemDoorName>_Type_XX=<string>    @{" More... " link SystemDoorName_Type_XX}
  <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX=<string>    @{" More... " link SystemDoorName_Door_XX}
  <SystemDoorName>_Param_XX=<string>   @{" More... " link SystemDoorName_Param_XX}
  <SystemDoorName>_Debug_XX=<boolean>  @{" More... " link SystemDoorName_Debug_XX}

  in the future the following options may be implemented:

  <SystemDoorName>_Priority_XX=<boolean>
  <SystemDoorName>_Access_XX=<number>

  <SystemDoorName>_Type_XX and <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX must ALWAYS
  be specified, but the other options are optional.

  Here's an example

  JoinConf_Type_1=HBBS
  JoinConf_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/User/JoinConference/JoinConference.HBBS {N} {O}
  JoinConf_Param_1=SYSTEM

  You may run two doors where one would normally be run like this:

  Extract_DIZ_Type_1=HBBS
  Extract_DIZ_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/System/ExtractDIZ/ExtractDIZ.HBBS {N} {O}
  Extract_DIZ_Param_1=EXTRACT
  Extract_DIZ_Type_2=HBBS
  Extract_DIZ_Door_2=HBBS:Doors/System/FileHistory/FileHistory.HBBS {N} {O}

  Note however, that the first door may set a flag that can prevent the
  second door from starting, this is down to each individual door.

  For a list of all the default door's provided with HBBS see
  @{"HBBS:Docs/Doors/DoorIndex.guide" link HBBS:Docs/Doors/DoorIndex.guide}

  If a door is replaced, it may allow you to start other system doors
  with different names other than the ones in the list above.  This is
  down to the door coder.

  Don't forget the order of precedence that system doors are looked for:

  HBBS:Conferences/<ConferenceName>/Commands/System
  HBBS:Nodes/Node<NodeNum>/Commands/System
  HBBS:Commands/System

  This allows you to only define things like the account editor on the local
  node!  Or you could set up one node that requires a user to have a specific
  access level, then you could define some command in that node's
  Commands/System file which then wouldn't be available to any other node
  or any user without that access level. Or to users with that access level
  on a different node..  Gosh, just think of those security prospects!


  System doors are defined in these ".../Commands/System" files like you
  define doors for /X's system doors in it's SYSCMD directory

@EndNode

@Node SystemDoorName_Type_XX "<SystemDoorName>_Type_XX"

  <SystemDoorName>_Type_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    Await_Type_1=HBBS

    This defines the type of door and how HBBS starts it.

    The supported types are:

    HBBS     - Denotes an HBBS door
    CLI      - Denotes a CLI program, set <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX the the
               name of a cli program.
    CLS      - Clears the screen, set <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX to CLS as well!
    ECHO     - Echo's the <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX setting to the screen.
    SSCREEN  - Display a special screen as defined by <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX
    PAUSE    - Displays the pause prompt as defined by <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX
    SCREEN   - Display a screen as defined by <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX
    BULLETIN - Display a bulletin as defined by <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX

    Note:

    Using the ECHO command to replace a system command in a particular
    conference or node is a good way of showing custom messages to users who
    are not allowed to access this door.

@EndNode

@Node SystemDoorName_Door_XX "<SystemDoorName>_Door_XX"

  <SystemDoorName>_Door_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    Await_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/System/AwaitConnect/AwaitConnect.HBBS {N} {O}

    This defines the door program or cli command and it's paramaters to use
    when this door is started.

    When <SystemDoorName>_Type_XX is set to HBBS the following
    string replacements are made to the command line before the command
    is executed:

    {N} - Replaced by the node number, this option is required
          for all HBBS doors so that the door can talk to the
          right instance of the Node program.
    {O} - This is replaced by any options the door is started with.
          For instance, one System or User door by call another System
          door with some paramaters.

    An interesting and usefull side affect of this string replacement is
    that you can do this:

    MyDoor_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/System/MyDoor/MyDoor_{N}.HBBS {N} {O}

    or

    MyDoor_Door_1=HBBS:Doors/System/MyDoorForNode{N}/MyDoor.HBBS {N} {O}

    So you can run seperate system door executables for a node, KEWL!
    great for door coders who can't be arsed to re-config the file
    HBBS:NodesX/Node/Commands/System!
    Most of the time though, you should use the HBBS:Nodes/NodeX/Commands/System
    file to do this, just though you'd like to see how kewl HBBS really is!

    Told you HBBS was great :-)

@EndNode

@Node SystemDoorName_Param_XX "<SystemDoorName>_Param_XX"

  <SystemDoorName>_Param_XX=<string>

    E.G.

    CheckTags_Param_1=LOGIN_CHECK

    This lets you specify the system options for a door.

    These options are in addition to any other options the door might
    have been called with.  This lets door codes write one door that
    can function as more than one door, for instance check out the
    configs for the Extract_DIZ and Update_DIZ system doors.

@EndNode

@Node SystemDoorName_Debug_XX "<SystemDoorName>_Debug_XX"

  <SystemDoorName>_Debug_XX=<boolean>

    E.G.

    MyNewDoorThatImCodingMysef_Debug_1=YES

    Default: NO

    When this option is specified HBBS will NOT run the door, instead
    it will display a message to the sysop via a CLI window and
    will prompt them to start the door.

    At this point the sysop can then in fact start ANY HBBS door program
    for that node.  Not just the one it is prompting for.

    This gives door coders the ability to run a debugger and step through
    each line of their code!

    See also @{"HBBS:BBSGlobal/Door_Timeout" link HBBS:Docs/Configuration/BBSGlobal.Guide/Door_Timeout}

@EndNode

